=== Appendix: complete fields[[CF]]

Let +\(S\)+ be a set. A [term]#metric# 
+\(d\)+ on +\(S\)+ is a function 
+\(d(x,y)\)+ with values in the real numbers which satisfies
(i) +\(d(x,y) \ge 0\)+ and +\(d(x,y) = 0\)+ if and only if +\(x  = y\)+, (ii)
+\(d(x,y) = d(y,x)\)+,
(iii) the [term]#triangle inequality#: +\(d(x,z) \le d(x,y) +
d(y,z)\)+.  A set together with a metric is called a [term]#metric
space#.  Given a metric space, the notion of Cauchy sequence is
defined.  A metric space is
[term]#complete# if every Cauchy sequence converges.
Given a metric space +\(S\)+, there is smallest complete metric space
+\(\bar S\)+ which contains +\(S\)+ as an open
dense set.  To define +\(S\)+, let +\(C(S)\)+ be the set of Cauchy
sequences of elements of +\(S\)+. Define an
equivalence relation on +\(C(S)\)+ by declaring 
the sequence +\((x_n)\)+ equivalent to the sequence
+\((y_n)\)+ if +\(d(x_n,y_n) \to 0\)+.  The completion of +\(S\)+ is
the quotient of +\(C(S)\)+ by this equivalence relation. We denote it
by +\(S_d\)+.  The map +\(a \mapsto (a,a,a,\ldots)\)+ which maps an
element of +\(S\)+ to the corresponding constant sequence identifies
+\(S\)+ with an open dense subset of +\(S_d\)+.
  
Now suppose that +\(K\)+ is a field with a [term]#valuation# +\(v\)+.  By
this we mean a function latexmath:[v: K \map R^+ ] satisfying (i) +\(v(x) \ge
0\)+,
(ii) +\(v(x) \ne 0\)+ if +\(x \ne 0\)+, (iii), if +\(v(x) \le 1\)+, 
then +\(v(1+x) \le a\)+ for all +\(x\)+ and a fixed +\(c \ge 1\)+, (iv) +\(v(xy)
= v(x)v(y)\)+. A valuation defines a metric by +\(d(x,y) = v(x-y)\)+. 
Denote the completion of a field with respect to a valuation by
+\(K_v\)+.

Regarding condition (iii): In familiar cases, +\(c=2\)+ or +\(c = 1\)+. If
+\(c = 2\)+, then the triangle inequality holds: +\(v(x +y) \le v(x) +
v(y)\)+.  If +\(c = 1\)+, then the _ultrametric inequality_ holds: +\(v(x
+ y) \le max(v(x), v(y))\)+.  In the first two examples below, the
valuation satisfies the triangle inequality.  In the last, it is
ultrametric.

.Examples
--
. The field of real numbers +\(\RR\)+ is the completion of the field
of rational numbers with respect to the valuation given by the
absolute value.

. The field of complex numbers +\(\CC\)+ is the completion with
respect to the absolute value of the field +\(\bar \QQ\)+ of algebraic
numbers.

. The field +\(\QQ_p\)+ of +\(p\)+-adic numbers is the completion with
respect to the [term]#p-adic valuation# of the rational numbers. 
To define the p-adic valuation,
write a rational number +\(x\)+ as +\(x = (a/b)p^n\)+
where neither +\(a\)+ nor +\(b\)+ is divisible by +\(p\)+.  Then
+\(v(x) = p^{-n}\)+.

--

